1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,610
Today, and I rejoice. We have good music in this church, don't we? I think you've been dulled by all the debris that's coming in around us, and I thought the moon was coming up, and I looked, and it was the sun. Nice, bright orange today, and that might look lovely, but what we're involved in over there is far from lovely.

2
00:00:29,610 --> 00:00:41,500
and minds that start something like that I can't figure out at all. Today I come this morning

3
00:00:41,500 --> 00:00:51,200
with a gift. Now this will be and it is this will be our last of the sub-series

4
00:00:51,200 --> 00:01:01,300
on those qualities that we need to have in our life for victorious living and it is a gift

5
00:01:01,300 --> 00:01:13,880
that is dynamic, it's real, and it will last forever. Don't you wish a car would? Last forever.

6
00:01:14,140 --> 00:01:22,090
The word used often is hope. We hear it used in mottos. People talk about it all the time.

7
00:01:22,510 --> 00:01:29,020
Hope springs eternal as if it was a natural phenomenon. You know, it just springs right up.

8
00:01:29,020 --> 00:01:39,890
even the billboards say, keep hope alive. Where there's life, there's hope, and where there's

9
00:01:39,890 --> 00:01:52,900
hope, there's life, and I don't mean Bob Hope. We use the words for many things. I've used it

10
00:01:52,900 --> 00:02:06,190
during these last few weeks. I said, you know, I really hope the Cubs and the Boston Red Sox

11
00:02:06,190 --> 00:02:18,250
will get into the playoffs, and they did, and then I said, I hope the Cubs and the Red Sox

12
00:02:18,250 --> 00:02:29,400
will win and be in the World Series, and the Cubs were taken care of. The Yankees came along and

13
00:02:29,400 --> 00:02:41,540
finished off the Red Sox, and I didn't really care who won the series. Well, not quite. I have a big

14
00:02:41,540 --> 00:02:55,390
grin on my face, six games, and the Florida Marlins were successful. That was a fulfillment

15
00:02:55,390 --> 00:03:06,220
of a hope, but that's short-lived. Then there's that hope that comes out of sheer enthusiasm and

16
00:03:06,220 --> 00:03:14,150
confidence. A man commuted into town on the train, commuter train. He got off to come home, and he was

17
00:03:14,150 --> 00:03:19,550
walking by the park he normally walked by and there was a ball field there and he was walking

18
00:03:19,550 --> 00:03:24,350
out there where the outfield is there was a fence there and there was a little boy standing out

19
00:03:24,350 --> 00:03:31,530
there it was time out and so he was there and so the man said well how you doing son and he said

20
00:03:31,530 --> 00:03:43,630
well well I'm doing I'm doing all right and he said not bad we're doing fine the man said who's

21
00:03:43,630 --> 00:03:54,240
ahead, and he said, they are, and he said, what's the score, and he said, 27 to nothing, and the man said,

22
00:03:54,280 --> 00:03:59,780
that's terrible, you must be terribly disappointed, he said, no, that's all right, we haven't even had

23
00:03:59,780 --> 00:04:09,750
our ups yet, now that's enthusiasm, and that's confidence, and there is hope, he didn't stay long

24
00:04:09,750 --> 00:04:21,640
enough to see it would work. Now I want to talk about serious hope, real hope. Hope is to our

25
00:04:21,640 --> 00:04:33,980
spirits what oxygen is to our lungs. We do not get oxygen into our lungs and we die. Your spirit dies

26
00:04:33,980 --> 00:04:47,090
when hope dies. They may not bury you for a while, but without hope, you're dead. I want to talk about

27
00:04:47,090 --> 00:04:56,010
that for a moment. A week ago, this past Saturday, there was another article in the Orange County

28
00:04:56,010 --> 00:05:08,970
Restaurant Register about a new worry in Afghanistan, and that worry is about AIDS.

29
00:05:12,100 --> 00:05:21,080
The story was about an Afghan woman who had no skills. She was not educated. She had come under

30
00:05:21,080 --> 00:05:31,230
the rule of the Taliban, and she was a thing. Things don't get educated. And then her husband

31
00:05:31,230 --> 00:05:40,220
was killed after a rocket fell in a Kabul marketplace, and it wasn't a rocket from us.

32
00:05:42,820 --> 00:05:53,800
Killed her husband, and she had five children to feed. She couldn't get an ordinary job

33
00:05:53,800 --> 00:06:04,060
because she was illiterate and women were prohibited from being educated. In order to feed

34
00:06:04,060 --> 00:06:14,350
her five children, she turned to prostitution. She was diagnosed with HIV and she said,

35
00:06:15,310 --> 00:06:27,780
I don't even know what HIV is. The women who go into prostitution don't worry about their life.

36
00:06:27,780 --> 00:06:38,060
they don't have any hope about their lives, and this woman then said, if we die, what does it

37
00:06:38,060 --> 00:06:50,220
matter, and if I live, what does it all mean? Here was a woman embedded, embedded in despair,

38
00:06:50,600 --> 00:07:00,310
and not a single ounce of hope available. Now, we don't have to go to Afghanistan to see that

39
00:07:00,310 --> 00:07:08,660
lived out. We see it around us, sometimes quietly, sometimes largely, but there are people

40
00:07:08,660 --> 00:07:18,170
that live without hope. So today, I want us to look at real hope. That's the gift I have today

41
00:07:18,170 --> 00:07:28,300
that I have brought this morning, and we find it in 1 Peter 1, 3 to 4. He writes, and by the way,

42
00:07:28,300 --> 00:07:31,480
Peter is known as the apostle of hope.

43
00:07:33,870 --> 00:07:38,670
It says, praise be to the God and Father of our Lord Jesus Christ.

44
00:07:39,360 --> 00:07:47,140
In his great mercy, he has given us new birth into a living hope,

45
00:07:47,320 --> 00:07:53,060
a hope that lasts forever through the resurrection of Jesus Christ from the dead

46
00:07:53,060 --> 00:07:58,890
and into an inheritance that can never perish, spoil, or fade,

47
00:07:58,890 --> 00:08:11,990
kept in heaven for you but operating in our lives now if we take that gift that's why i said i have

48
00:08:11,990 --> 00:08:22,830
a gift for you this morning only if you take it we know that we live in a broken world a hurting

49
00:08:22,830 --> 00:08:31,050
world a troubling world and a desperate world if you don't believe me just read the paper they tell

50
00:08:31,050 --> 00:08:40,560
all about that stuff. Peter lived in this kind of world too, and so we wrote to a people who

51
00:08:40,560 --> 00:08:46,820
were involved in great persecution and hostility. Peter is known as, as I said, as the apostle of

52
00:08:46,820 --> 00:08:56,020
hope, and this letter is a letter of radiant hope and triumphant even in the middle of suffering.

53
00:08:57,430 --> 00:09:05,610
This is what we need in our world today because many of around us have no hope. Let me tell you

54
00:09:05,610 --> 00:09:13,100
about a young lady. We were pastoring in Pasadena, right across from the Pasadena City College.

55
00:09:14,400 --> 00:09:20,320
We were on that corner there. There was a bus stop. I had gotten there early, just a little

56
00:09:20,320 --> 00:09:26,360
after seven. That was not my usual time to get there. I had a lot of things to do, and I went

57
00:09:26,360 --> 00:09:33,900
to my study. All the doors were locked, and I just got started, and there was a knock on the study

58
00:09:33,900 --> 00:09:40,820
door. I couldn't figure that one out, because everything was locked, so I opened the door, and

59
00:09:40,820 --> 00:09:48,910
in she walked. Behind her was the smiling face of the custodian, Merlin, and he said,

60
00:09:49,670 --> 00:09:55,700
Pastor, this young lady just got off the bus, and she wants to talk to the reverend,

61
00:09:56,140 --> 00:10:07,070
and I knew you would want to talk with her. My eyes and my facial expression did not communicate

62
00:10:07,070 --> 00:10:17,500
that kind of joy to Merlin, but I turned around, and she was standing there, and I asked, told her

63
00:10:17,500 --> 00:10:29,450
she could please be seated, and I said, do you want to talk? She said yes. I looked at her.

64
00:10:30,910 --> 00:10:37,450
She had a cocktail dress on. It was torn in the hem. It was torn up here around the neck a little.

65
00:10:37,450 --> 00:10:44,690
whatever makeup she had was now a disaster and most of it was gone. There were little rivulets

66
00:10:44,690 --> 00:10:51,230
that had left their traces on her face and I knew she had been in the midst of tears somewhere

67
00:10:51,230 --> 00:11:00,600
in that night. It was apparent that she had been up all night and she told me her story.

68
00:11:02,040 --> 00:11:08,040
Pregnant at 15, gave birth to a child. Right after that she was pregnant again,

69
00:11:08,040 --> 00:11:11,200
not the same father

70
00:11:11,200 --> 00:11:13,840
both of them just moved on

71
00:11:13,840 --> 00:11:15,540
and there she was

72
00:11:15,540 --> 00:11:17,080
living with her mother in Texas

73
00:11:17,080 --> 00:11:20,870
and just shortly after

74
00:11:20,870 --> 00:11:22,650
that baby was born

75
00:11:22,650 --> 00:11:24,970
maybe 8 or 9 months

76
00:11:24,970 --> 00:11:26,810
her mother came home

77
00:11:26,810 --> 00:11:28,150
because her mother was working

78
00:11:28,150 --> 00:11:30,010
and she came in

79
00:11:30,010 --> 00:11:32,400
not finding her daughter

80
00:11:32,400 --> 00:11:34,080
but finding a note

81
00:11:34,080 --> 00:11:37,550
and it said I can't take this anymore

82
00:11:37,550 --> 00:11:39,480
I am leaving

83
00:11:39,480 --> 00:11:41,820
that was it

84
00:11:41,820 --> 00:11:51,670
and she left. That was about a year and a half to two years from the time she left and the time I

85
00:11:51,670 --> 00:12:00,600
talked, and she had never contacted her mother. She came to L.A. and the Hollywood area, I suppose,

86
00:12:01,180 --> 00:12:10,790
full of some kind of hope, but that spiraled downward real quickly, and she went from one

87
00:12:10,790 --> 00:12:18,340
partner to another partner, and it was one of those sordid, sordid tales of a lost soul.

88
00:12:20,280 --> 00:12:27,690
And the night before I talked with her, she had been taken to a party with obvious expectations,

89
00:12:28,390 --> 00:12:40,520
and it went on and on, and finally someone said to her, you put out or you get out,

90
00:12:40,520 --> 00:12:50,340
and she left. She had a little bag that she had carried there. It wasn't much bigger than to take

91
00:12:50,340 --> 00:12:58,500
a change of clothes, and she left, and the shoes she had on were not walking shoes,

92
00:12:59,460 --> 00:13:07,120
those spiked heels. She walked. I don't know when she left in the morning, but she walked for long

93
00:13:07,120 --> 00:13:15,990
ways. She walked long enough east of Pasadena to catch that first bus that broke in the morning,

94
00:13:16,490 --> 00:13:30,020
and she got to our place just about almost when I got there, and she saw the sign. She saw the

95
00:13:30,020 --> 00:13:34,160
church. She didn't know where she was going. She just knew she had to get out of there,

96
00:13:34,160 --> 00:13:46,170
and she saw Merlin and she asked to see me and she told me her story and then she looked at me

97
00:13:46,170 --> 00:13:55,790
and she looked at me through some of the oldest eyes I had ever seen in my life and it struck me

98
00:13:55,790 --> 00:14:06,960
like a hammer because our daughter Deanne was just the age of this 18-19 year old girl. She

99
00:14:06,960 --> 00:14:20,710
looked at me and said, is there any hope? Nineteen years old. Is there any hope? And so we talked and

100
00:14:20,710 --> 00:14:31,440
we shared. And in the midst of that, God seemed to move and work. And I told her about the only hope

101
00:14:31,440 --> 00:14:39,540
that would work in her life. And we talked about that, talked about the timing, talked about isn't

102
00:14:39,540 --> 00:14:49,450
a time to let go and let God do a work in your life. And we talked about hope. We had prayer.

103
00:14:50,530 --> 00:14:58,420
She made a confession. And then when that was over, she looked up at me with tears in her eyes

104
00:14:58,420 --> 00:15:10,580
and she said, can I call my mom? Hadn't contacted her mother in all this time. I said, be my guest.

105
00:15:10,580 --> 00:15:22,530
and she called and I heard a voice that answered the phone and we'll call this young lady Alice

106
00:15:22,530 --> 00:15:38,130
and Alice said mom this is Alice first clue that she was even in existence I don't know what the

107
00:15:38,130 --> 00:15:47,270
mother said but I heard the shout and the exultation and then she said mom can I come home

108
00:15:47,270 --> 00:15:58,090
I want to be your daughter and I want to be a mother we went and got something to eat we both

109
00:15:58,090 --> 00:16:07,060
went down to the bus stop she went and changed from that cocktail dress into some little bit

110
00:16:07,060 --> 00:16:16,100
clothes that she had there, got a ticket to Texas, and I stayed with her until the bus came.

111
00:16:17,380 --> 00:16:24,000
Then I watched that bus as it pulled out, and I saw that young woman look out the bus, finally

112
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:35,120
spotted me, and I saw her lips moving to say, thank you so much, and I waited until the bus

113
00:16:35,120 --> 00:16:44,160
was out of sight. All the stuff that was busy business for me was gone by the way because of

114
00:16:44,160 --> 00:16:54,220
a woman who had found hope, real honest to goodness hope, and we praise God for it. Unfortunately,

115
00:16:54,220 --> 00:17:03,930
there are some false hopes. We hear them over the telemarketers. We see them in the paper,

116
00:17:03,930 --> 00:17:11,140
in the advertisements you even see them in great big billboards I was driving down from Bakersfield

117
00:17:11,140 --> 00:17:15,840
when I was a young pastor and I'd been asked to serve on the state convention board because I was

118
00:17:15,840 --> 00:17:21,420
representing youth I was a minister of youth and so I was at going to the first meeting at Fifth

119
00:17:21,420 --> 00:17:26,960
and Olive in downtown Los Angeles and I'd never been there before and I got the map and I knew

120
00:17:26,960 --> 00:17:32,120
where I was going now and I looked for that off-ramp and I made the off-ramp and the turn

121
00:17:32,120 --> 00:17:35,440
to go down to Olive Drive and Olive Street,

122
00:17:36,510 --> 00:17:38,890
and there in front of me was a building and a sign.

123
00:17:39,700 --> 00:17:41,360
The sign was not on a billboard.

124
00:17:41,720 --> 00:17:43,960
It was painted right on that red brick building.

125
00:17:44,360 --> 00:17:45,640
It was there forever.

126
00:17:46,650 --> 00:17:48,530
People that were on the freeway could see it,

127
00:17:48,570 --> 00:17:52,000
but I could see it straight on when I made the turn.

128
00:17:52,620 --> 00:17:53,880
The sign said,

129
00:17:55,030 --> 00:17:59,840
borrow enough to get you completely out of debt.

130
00:17:59,840 --> 00:18:11,220
duh it took me a few turns of the wheel to get control again as the truth of that hit me

131
00:18:11,220 --> 00:18:22,240
bar enough to get completely out of debt i thought about when i knew we were going to be doing this

132
00:18:22,240 --> 00:18:29,100
and preaching in this series thought about hope i came up with three effects of a living hope

133
00:18:29,100 --> 00:18:41,020
three of them one with hope as your base you face life differently I didn't say everything

134
00:18:41,020 --> 00:18:49,960
that bothered you was removed I said with hope in Jesus Christ a living hope because he gave that to

135
00:18:49,960 --> 00:19:01,490
us the gift as your base you face life differently you look at it differently I'll explain that in a

136
00:19:01,490 --> 00:19:10,800
moment. Secondly, hope is energizing. There is an energy that comes from hope, and I'll tell you

137
00:19:10,800 --> 00:19:19,010
what that does. Hope obliterates despair. They can't live in the same room. Hope comes into your

138
00:19:19,010 --> 00:19:29,150
life, and it obliterates, does away with despair. He doesn't do away with the circumstances. He does

139
00:19:29,150 --> 00:19:38,620
away with despair. It obliterates it because our hope is based upon what God has done,

140
00:19:38,740 --> 00:19:45,820
not on our own efforts or wishful thinking. And three, and I think this is almost the most

141
00:19:45,820 --> 00:19:58,130
important, with a living hope, we cease to be a victim and we become a victor. Think of Paul and

142
00:19:58,130 --> 00:20:06,210
Silas in jail? They were victims? I don't think so. They were in jail. That was a fact. They sang

143
00:20:06,210 --> 00:20:15,200
the praise hymns, and they came out a victor along with the jailer and along with the family

144
00:20:15,200 --> 00:20:23,530
and the children. They came out of that jail, the jail of their own doing with the jailer and the

145
00:20:23,530 --> 00:20:34,340
family, but they were not victims. They were victors. Now, how is that hope lived out?

146
00:20:34,800 --> 00:20:46,010
I thought you'd never ask. I want to tell you about my father. My father was an oil worker,

147
00:20:46,790 --> 00:20:54,260
came from Texas, got here, and way out in the boonies around Taft, his father was in the oil

148
00:20:54,260 --> 00:20:59,320
fields. He went to the eighth grade, went to work in the oil fields. Part of that was to help his

149
00:20:59,320 --> 00:21:07,840
brother get through college. And that's all he did. And he didn't mind it at all. In fact,

150
00:21:07,860 --> 00:21:13,690
he liked it very much. He was in a well-pulling crew at that time, and those were the ones that

151
00:21:13,690 --> 00:21:18,290
repair the wells. And maybe you've seen them driving up and down Bastion Cherry with some

152
00:21:18,290 --> 00:21:26,030
rods sticking up in the air, and they were fixing the pumping wells. He was in that truck on the

153
00:21:26,030 --> 00:21:32,210
back with another man, and the back was full of tools. A drunk driver came down that Pozo Creek

154
00:21:32,210 --> 00:21:39,070
Road, which was basically dirt and a little asphalt, pushed the truck over to the side and

155
00:21:39,070 --> 00:21:46,290
the shoulders. The truck rolled, and all those tools, all those boxes in the back rolled with

156
00:21:46,290 --> 00:21:57,220
my father and the other man, and at that moment in time, he became a paraplegic at 41, desperately

157
00:21:57,220 --> 00:22:06,940
ill. Broken bones, I don't want to even name them. He didn't gain real consciousness for 45 days,

158
00:22:07,540 --> 00:22:15,530
six months in the hospital. Now, that would put anyone down the trail of despair. He could no

159
00:22:15,530 --> 00:22:24,600
longer do, and what he liked to do was work. But you know what he said? He said, God saved my life

160
00:22:24,600 --> 00:22:34,600
for a purpose, and I'm going to find out what that purpose is. Went back to school,

161
00:22:35,100 --> 00:22:39,700
got a high school diploma, did some things, employed by the Shell Oil Company for life,

162
00:22:39,700 --> 00:22:48,090
as long as he could do it, and he was a living testimony of hope. There was not a despair bone

163
00:22:48,090 --> 00:22:56,370
in his body. He loved the Lord, and he loved people, and what could have been a disaster

164
00:22:56,370 --> 00:23:05,960
for him, became a means by which his own faith was strengthened, and he was that person of hope.

165
00:23:05,960 --> 00:23:15,200
He lived with us. We know about that. That's how those things work. He faced life differently.

166
00:23:15,860 --> 00:23:23,280
Hope was energizing for him, and with a living hope, my father ceased to be a victim. He was

167
00:23:23,280 --> 00:23:34,120
the victor as he walked out of a doctor's office on his crutches seven years after the doctor said

168
00:23:34,120 --> 00:23:39,800
you will never walk again and you will be in a wheelchair for the rest of your life and my father

169
00:23:39,800 --> 00:23:46,720
said no I won't and he said if you walk I'll quit my practice he walked in seven years later and the

170
00:23:46,720 --> 00:23:57,020
first words he said was doc when are you going to resign that was the kind of person with a hope

171
00:23:59,370 --> 00:24:02,250
There may come times when you become the instrument

172
00:24:02,250 --> 00:24:05,520
through which the living hope is given to another.

173
00:24:06,880 --> 00:24:12,070
I had an experience some time ago.

174
00:24:13,770 --> 00:24:19,780
I and another minister was asked to be on a program called Let's Talk.

175
00:24:20,340 --> 00:24:22,860
Those were in the days when the radio stations

176
00:24:22,860 --> 00:24:28,290
would donate free time to charitable organizations

177
00:24:28,290 --> 00:24:29,350
and that kind of thing.

178
00:24:30,190 --> 00:24:33,310
And so this station decided to put all they had

179
00:24:33,310 --> 00:24:36,710
into one three-hour block once a week.

180
00:24:37,840 --> 00:24:40,260
And the station was KRLA.

181
00:24:40,960 --> 00:24:43,680
Now, KRLA now is a talk show.

182
00:24:44,620 --> 00:24:48,000
Do you know what KRLA was at that time in the 60s?

183
00:24:48,680 --> 00:24:54,420
It was a hard rock and roll, beat-em-up kind of music

184
00:24:54,420 --> 00:24:58,520
with a shouting, almost insane disc jockey.

185
00:24:58,520 --> 00:25:08,040
and he was on there till nine o'clock and after nine guess who showed up two baptist preachers

186
00:25:08,040 --> 00:25:15,430
on that station and you hear that music and he shouted as he would often listen to me on and

187
00:25:15,430 --> 00:25:21,570
he gave all that stuff and with another roar and and that music and then some soft music came on

188
00:25:21,570 --> 00:25:28,490
and then these two preachers on let's talk there was no screener we just took it right cold

189
00:25:28,490 --> 00:25:32,280
and we were there from nine to midnight.

190
00:25:33,250 --> 00:25:36,150
I preached morning service, evening service,

191
00:25:36,450 --> 00:25:40,610
got over there in time to take off my coat and get going.

192
00:25:41,910 --> 00:25:43,750
About in the middle of that, on one evening,

193
00:25:43,870 --> 00:25:44,810
there was a phone call.

194
00:25:45,950 --> 00:25:48,850
Usually we ask for names and we did

195
00:25:48,850 --> 00:25:51,820
and the voice was kind of a younger woman

196
00:25:51,820 --> 00:25:53,740
and she said, I'm not going to give you my name.

197
00:25:54,490 --> 00:25:56,470
I said, well, what area do you live in?

198
00:25:56,530 --> 00:25:58,190
She said, I'm not going to tell you that either.

199
00:25:58,190 --> 00:26:08,320
